:: Turtle 

<blockquote>You gave it all up to machines so quickly.</blockquote>

That's what earth said: that we had short-sold our entire species' skills for the benefit of machines. Early science-fiction television culture pointed to this well after the first major critiques, but still, it was there: delegation of human ingenuity followed by contempt and ridicule for machine productions. 

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/SySZdvsFYt4?si=I8DZgZzuUFNXk8S5" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>

Delegation and devaluation of skill were rarely so obvious than in the scene above, taken from <em>Star Trek, The Next Generation,</em> a US television series that aired from 1987 to 1994. 

Star Trek, along with the Star Wars franchise both went on for hundreds of years, in ways and others. Both had tremendous influence on the rich and powerful exposed to them. The first intergalacitic ships were named after the series ships. 

Episodes explored many themes from Mediterranean, European, and North American settlerized literature, each of them homing on one, or a few, individual experiences. Usually centered around a captain and the higher officer crew (along with one or two ensign oddballs), the series exemplified the actions of the many in the decisions of the few.

The urge to conquer turned the ultra rich into Earth's enemies. Star Trek varnished their ambitions and shaped their technological might.

Despite the warp drives and replicators acting as technological magic wands of the future, the ultra rich never fared far. At most, Earth observed, their speeds and powers didn't even come to the feet of the noblest of turtles.

